# {{lb|en|topology}} For a specified [[topological space]], the [[group]] whose [[element]]s are [[homotopy]] [[class]]es of loops ([[image]]s of some arbitrary [[closed]] [[interval]] whose [[endpoint]]s are both [[map]]ped to a designated [[point]]) and whose group [[operation]] is [[concatenation]].
#* '''1991''', {{w|William S. Massey}}, ''A Basic Course in Algebraic Topology'', Springer, [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=svbU9nxi2xQC&pg=PA35&dq=%22fundamental+group%22%7C%22fundamental+groups%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimjaOYhM3tAhX94zgGHcQdA7AQ6AEwEnoECD8QAg#v=onepage&q=%22fundamental%20group%22%7C%22fundamental%20groups%22&f=false page 35],
#*: From the definition it will be clear the group is a topological invariant of ''X''; i.e., if two spaces are homeomorphic, their '''fundamental groups''' are isomorphic.
#* '''2011''', John Coates, Minhyong Kim, Florian Pop, Mohamed Saïdi, Peter Schneider (editors), ''Non-abelian '''Fundamental Groups''' and Iwasawa Theory'', {{w|Cambridge University Press}}, [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=IE1ntkuVdGgC&pg=PR7&dq=%22fundamental+group%22%7C%22fundamental+groups%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimjaOYhM3tAhX94zgGHcQdA7AQ6AEwB3oECCgQAg#v=onepage&q=%22fundamental%20group%22%7C%22fundamental%20groups%22&f=false page vii],
#*: Therein came into focus the far-reaching vision that the perspective of non-abelian '''fundamental groups''' could lead to a fundamentally new understanding of deep arithmetic phenomena, including the arithmetic theory of moduli and Diophantine finiteness on hyperbolic curves.
#* '''2012''', Jakob Stix (editor), ''The Arithmetic of '''Fundamental Groups''': PIA 2010'', Springer, [https://books.google.com.au/books?id=0qKgVKmQ4PIC&pg=PR9&dq=%22fundamental+group%22%7C%22fundamental+groups%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimjaOYhM3tAhX94zgGHcQdA7AQ6AEwBnoECCcQAg#v=onepage&q=%22fundamental%20group%22%7C%22fundamental%20groups%22&f=false page ix],
